I don't think users know what break points are, why they're important, or how to effectively set them. If possible, I'd like to use javascript to automatically update the breakpoints in the header css based on the actual measured width of the title text, nav bar, etc.

Here's some code I came up with that could help. 

```javascript

// get maximum expanded size of element
const maxWidth = (selector) => {
  const element = document.querySelector(selector);
  element.style.minWidth = "max-content";
  const width = element.clientWidth;
  element.style.minWidth = "";
  return width;
};

// listen to media query and update data attribute
const makeQuery = (width, element, attr) => {
  const query = window.matchMedia(`(max-width: ${width}px)`);
  const updateAttr = () => element.setAttribute("data-" + attr, query.matches);
  updateAttr();
  query.addEventListener("change", updateAttr);
};
```

I've experimented with using this to set data attributes on the header, but that comes with some problems, like FOUC. I'd rather actually find the style in the stylesheet and update it if possible.

I'm marking this as a "super-enhancement" because it adds a lot of complexity and possibly brittleness, so I'm not sure if I'm ultimately going to do it. This might just have to be something I explain thoroughly in the docs, and hope the users remember to do it every time they change their header.

